Genomic SEM factor analysis: sensitivity follow-up analyses

We take the model that showed the best fit and carry it forward to do sensitivity and robustness analyses. We used the EFA-based 4-factor model, the bifactor per substance, and bifactor per trait type.

Odd versus even chromosomes

13. EFA 4 factor - Even/ odd chromosomes

We used the whole genome to fit both EFA and CFA models for practical and theoretical reasons. If it is true that for many traits the genetic signal is rather localized (rather than spread out evenly across the genome) this would give a different factor structure in different chromosome subsets. To check this, we compare the factor structure for even and odd chromosomes separately. Indeed, the factor structure is quite different.

EFA for even:

12. EFA 4 factor - Varimax rotated

To check, we tried a varimax rotation on the 4-factor EFA. The solution suggested by the EFA is not too different. Fitting this model in CFA while forcing the factors to be orthogonal (uncorrelated) gives a rather high SRMR, though CFI is excellent. The factor solution seems a bit less intuitive, and the path estimates are very wild.

CFA:

load('data/mldsc_29May2023.14.TOT.RData')

CFA <- '
F1 =~ NA*SMKCES + PACKYE + SMKDEP + ALCDEP + SMKAGE + COCDEP + ALCFRQ + SMKINI
F2 =~ NA*SMKAGE + CANDEP + COCDEP + OPIODEP + CANEV + SMKINI
F3 =~ NA*ALCDEP + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP
F4 =~ NA*CANDEP + CANEV + CANFL + SMKINI

F1~~1*F1
F2~~1*F2
F3~~1*F3
F4~~1*F4

F1~~0*F2 
F1~~0*F3 
F1~~0*F4
F2~~0*F3
F2~~0*F4
F3~~0*F4

a > .001
ALCDEP ~~ a*ALCDEP

b > .001
CANFL ~~ b*CANFL

c > .001
OPIODEP ~~ c*OPIODEP
'

#run the model

Plot EFA 4 factor - Varimax rotated

semPlotModel_GSEM=function(gsem.object=GWISoutput , est.label="STD_All"){ 
      
       object=gsem.object$results
       object$free=0
       numb=1:length(which(object$op!="~~"))
       object$free[which(object$op!="~~")]=numb
       varNames <- lavaanNames(object, type = "ov")
       factNames <- lavaanNames(object, type = "lv")
       factNames <- factNames[!factNames %in% varNames]
       n <- length(varNames)
       k <- length(factNames)
       if (is.null(object$label)) 
         object$label <- rep("", nrow(object))
       semModel <- new("semPlotModel")
       object$est <- object[,est.label]
       object$se <- object[,"STD_Genotype_SE"]
       
       if (is.null(object$group)) 
         object$group <- ""
       semModel@Pars <- data.frame(label = object$label, lhs = ifelse(object$op == 
                                                                        "~" | object$op == "~1", object$rhs, object$lhs), edge = "--", 
                                   rhs = ifelse(object$op == "~" | object$op == "~1", object$lhs, 
                                                object$rhs), est = object$est, std = NA, group = object$group, 
                                   fixed = object$free==0, par = object$free, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~~"] <- "<->"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~*~"] <- "<->"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~"] <- "~>"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "=~"] <- "->"
       semModel@Pars$edge[object$op == "~1"] <- "int"
       semModel@Pars$edge[grepl("\\|", object$op)] <- "|"
       semModel@Thresholds <- semModel@Pars[grepl("\\|", semModel@Pars$edge), 
                                            -(3:4)]
       semModel@Pars <- semModel@Pars[!object$op %in% c(":=", "<", 
                                                        ">", "==", "|", "<", ">"), ]
       semModel@Vars <- data.frame(name = c(varNames, factNames), 
                                   manifest = c(varNames, factNames) %in% varNames, exogenous = NA, 
                                   stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
       semModel@ObsCovs <- list()
       semModel@ImpCovs <- list()
       semModel@Computed <- FALSE
       semModel@Original <- list(object)
       return(semModel)
       
}

Index-event bias adjusted

11. EFA 4 factor - Index-event adjusted

We explore if the Hunter-slope adjusted summary statistics show a different clustering than the unadjusted ones, again extracting 4 factors. The factor structure is somewhat different, but the fit is still decent. Of all models, I think this is the only one where smoking age has a positive loading on a factor (same direction as other indicators).

load('data/mldsc_29May2023.hunted.age.14.TOT.RData')

19. Per substance - Bifactor HDL

Now we repeat the model that fit the data best (bifactor - per substance) with an HDL-based covariance structure (instead of LDSC). The covariance of opioid dependence could not be estimated and is not included in these models. Therefore, there is no DRG factor and COCDEP is included only in the general G factor. As with the bias-adjusted model, the correlation between SMK and CAN has to be restricted <.99. The fit of the S-1 model without the SMK factor is bad, and CANDEP does not load on the cannabis factor.

load("data/hdl_10January2024.14.RData")

bif <- 'G =~ NA*PACKYE + SMKCES + SMKDEP + SMKAGE + SMKINI + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP + ALCDEP + CANEV + CANFL + CANDEP + COCDEP

SMK =~ NA*PACKYE + SMKCES + SMKDEP + SMKAGE + SMKINI 
ALC =~ NA*ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP + ALCDEP 
CAN =~ NA*CANEV + CANFL + CANDEP 

G ~~ 0*SMK + 0*ALC + 0*CAN

G~~1*G
SMK~~1*SMK
ALC~~1*ALC
CAN~~1*CAN

a>.001
   ALCP~~a*ALCP
  
b>.001  
  CANEV~~b*CANEV
  
c>-.99
  CAN~~c*SMK
'

#run the model

23. Per stage - Bifactor uncorrelated

We fit the per stage bifactor model while removing the correlation between the factors. The fit decreases in respect to the correlated bifactor.

bif <- 'G =~ NA*SMKINI + SMKAGE + CANEV + PACKYE + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP + CANFL + SMKDEP + ALCDEP + CANDEP + COCDEP + OPIODEP

INI =~ NA*SMKINI + SMKAGE + CANEV
FRQ =~ NA*PACKYE + ALCCON + ALCFRQ + ALCP + CANFL
DEP =~ NA*SMKDEP + ALCDEP + CANDEP + COCDEP + OPIODEP

G ~~ 0*INI + 0*FRQ + 0*DEP
INI ~~ 0*FRQ + 0*DEP
FRQ ~~ 0*DEP

G~~1*G
INI~~1*INI
FRQ~~1*FRQ
DEP~~1*DEP
'

#run the model
fit <- usermodel(ldscOut, estimation = "DWLS", model = bif, CFIcalc = TRUE)
fitlabel <- paste0("CFI = ", round(fit$modelfit$CFI,3), ", SRMR = ", round(fit$modelfit$SRMR,3), ", AIC = ", round(fit$modelfit$AIC), ", Chisq = ", round(fit$modelfit$chisq))
